history.content:
Given a good background in EECS16AB, STAT140, CS70, CS61A, you are well prepared for Shewchuk's 189. In addition, if you have taken 189 and stat 140, there is not much need to take data100.

----

@OP, I've heard EECS 127 is great to take alongside Shewchuck's 189, so you may want to look into that

I'm admittedly biased here, but I disagree with the notion that there isn't a need to take data 100  if one has taken prob 140 and cs 189. While I agree that there's plenty of overlap between the machine learning portion of data 100 and 189, there is no part of either 189/140 where you will learn about things like regex, data cleaning, Eda, visualisation, pandas, or the data science life cycle. Additionally, given that data 100 devotes more time to linear and logistic regression than 189 does, it's reasonable to say it introduces a more robust foundation to these topics than 189 in at least some regards
Given a good background in EECS16AB, STAT140, CS70, CS61A, you are well prepared for Shewchuk's 189. In addition, if you have taken 189 and stat 140, there is not much need to take data100.

since 170 is in flux, I'm considering taking 189 for Spring just in case 170 gets cancelled.  I'm a 2nd year CS person but possibly graduating next year, did/doing reasonably well in 16AB, 70 and STAT 140.  Calc including MVC was all done before arriving.  It would be my first upper division CS course (outside of Data 100).  Is it possibly too early to take the class?
history.subject: is there a maturity aspect to 189?
